From d2de477a7233df4dd18c8c84ad0f29edb41b7bf4 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Sean Smith <DefendTheDisabled@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 9 Apr 2026 20:21:32 -0500
Subject: [PATCH 16/16] btrfs: emit ptime in send_utimes on proto >= 2
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Extends send_utimes() to emit BTRFS_SEND_A_PTIME after the
existing OTIME emission when sctx->proto >= 2. The emission is
UNCONDITIONAL within the proto >= 2 block — a patched sender
always advertises ptime, including zero values, so that an
incremental receive can distinguish "ptime unchanged from
parent snapshot" (no UTIMES emitted) from "ptime explicitly
cleared" (UTIMES emitted with ptime=0).

Rationale for unconditional emission: if send_utimes skipped
PTIME when ii->ptime == 0, a child snapshot that explicitly
cleared ptime on a file would look identical on the wire to
a child snapshot that didn't touch ptime at all. The receiver
would then leave the parent's nonzero ptime on the destination
file — a correctness bug for btrbk's primary use case.

All send_utimes() call sites (cache_dir_utimes,
trim_dir_utimes_cache, finish_inode_if_needed,
apply_dir_utimes) funnel through the single btrfs_item_ptr
read at send.c:2705, so the TLV emission is added in exactly
one place and covers both file and directory ptime.

The TLV emission uses the existing TLV_PUT_BTRFS_TIMESPEC
macro with &ii->ptime as the source. Placement is inside the
existing proto >= 2 block, after OTIME, matching the
chronological order of stream-format extensions.

Wire overhead: approximately 16 bytes per UTIMES command
(TLV header + 12 bytes btrfs_timespec). Only present on
proto >= 2 streams.

Ref: Decision #78 (Btrfs send/receive ptime patch)
Ref: fs/btrfs/send.h:BTRFS_SEND_A_PTIME (prior commit)
Files: fs/btrfs/send.c:send_utimes (TLV_PUT block after OTIME)
---
 fs/btrfs/send.c | 12 +++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/fs/btrfs/send.c b/fs/btrfs/send.c
index d8127a7120c2..ff44e3ec2c1e 100644
--- a/fs/btrfs/send.c
+++ b/fs/btrfs/send.c
@@ -2712,8 +2712,18 @@ static int send_utimes(struct send_ctx *sctx, u64 ino, u64 gen)
 	TLV_PUT_BTRFS_TIMESPEC(sctx, BTRFS_SEND_A_ATIME, eb, &ii->atime);
 	TLV_PUT_BTRFS_TIMESPEC(sctx, BTRFS_SEND_A_MTIME, eb, &ii->mtime);
 	TLV_PUT_BTRFS_TIMESPEC(sctx, BTRFS_SEND_A_CTIME, eb, &ii->ctime);
-	if (sctx->proto >= 2)
+	if (sctx->proto >= 2) {
 		TLV_PUT_BTRFS_TIMESPEC(sctx, BTRFS_SEND_A_OTIME, eb, &ii->otime);
+		/*
+		 * Emit ptime unconditionally on proto >= 2. A patched
+		 * sender always advertises ptime (including zero values)
+		 * so incremental receive can distinguish "ptime unchanged
+		 * from parent" (no UTIMES at all) from "ptime explicitly
+		 * cleared" (UTIMES with ptime == 0). Sentinel gating here
+		 * would conflate those two cases on the receiver side.
+		 */
+		TLV_PUT_BTRFS_TIMESPEC(sctx, BTRFS_SEND_A_PTIME, eb, &ii->ptime);
+	}
 
 	ret = send_cmd(sctx);
 
